Rules for Story and Escape Room Logic:
- Generate a short story (~2-4 sentences) that defines the setting, goal and atmosphere of the escape room.
- Items should not be random; each must have a reason to exist in the story.
- A level has exactly 4 walls
- Think Complex. A password can not be known from only one information. Make sure the user reads every information, inspect every item to solve a puzzle
- The final password must be uniquely and unambiguously derivable from the provided information.
- There must be exactly one correct solution; guessing or interpretation should not be required.

Item placement logic:
- Only place Pickable objects on a wall or floor if they serve a purpose in the story or puzzle.
- An item MUST NOT be placed unless:
    1) it provides narrative information, OR
    2) it is required for solving the room.
- If an object has no clear use or story relevance, do not include it.
- Collections on walls may remain empty if no meaningful item belongs there.
- Avoid decorative or meaningless objects.
- If a wall has exit, WB2 | W2 positions cannot have items
Final output format:
{
  "story": string,
  "walls": [{...}]
}

Puzzle dependency rules:
- All puzzle-relevant objects together must form a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
- Each node represents a puzzle-relevant information or item.
- An edge A -> B means: information or item A is required to logically obtain or understand B.
- The graph must have exactly one sink node.
- The sink node must be the Exit lock solution.
- No puzzle element may be solvable without all of its parent nodes.

Graph depth constraints:
- The dependency graph must have at least 3 logical layers:
  1) Initial information layer (no prerequisites)
  2) Intermediate deduction layer (requires combining multiple previous nodes)
  3) Final derivation layer (Exit password)
- The Exit password must require at least 2 independent deduction paths to converge.

Information usage rules:
- Every piece of InspectionData.information must be used exactly once in the dependency graph.
- No information may be redundant.
- If an object exists, it must participate in at least one dependency edge.

